cpufreq/amd-pstate: dynamically bias EPP to performance on busy CPUs

In active (EPP) mode the platform autonomously picks the operating point
between min_perf and max_perf, biased by the EPP hint, and the kernel only
rewrites the CPPC request on policy/limit changes. A workload dominated by
one mostly-busy thread that takes frequent short sleeps -- e.g. a game
render thread blocking on a futex waiting for the GPU or a worker thread
every frame -- defeats the platform's utilization tracking: each sleep
decays the hardware's performance signal, so post-wakeup bursts start at a
low operating point and the frame-time tail inflates even though the CPU is
~100% busy at the frame timescale.

Measured on a Steam Deck (Van Gogh APU, EPP=balance_performance) running the
Civ VI graphics benchmark, which is single-thread CPU-bound (one render
thread ~98% busy, GPU ~3% busy). The busy core's median frequency sat at
2.43 GHz -- below 90% of fmax 58% of the time, bimodal 2.4/3.5 GHz -- despite
98% utilization. Globally forcing EPP=performance lifts the median to
3.5 GHz and cuts frame-time p999 ~40% with the 1%-low fps up ~16%, but it
does so on every core and every workload.

This adds an opt-in per-core mechanism that applies the same EPP=performance
lever, but only to a core that has recently been busy, via a cpufreq
update-util hook (mirroring intel_pstate's hwp_boost). C0 residency is
sampled every 10 ms from delta-MPERF/delta-TSC; once a core is >=50% busy it
is held for a 300 ms decay window, over which its EPP byte in
MSR_AMD_CPPC_REQ is set to AMD_CPPC_EPP_PERFORMANCE and then restored to the
policy EPP when the core goes idle. hwp_boost keys off SCHED_CPUFREQ_IOWAIT,
which futex/GPU-fence waits never set, so a residency trigger is used here
instead.

An earlier version of this raised min_perf to nominal_perf on a busy core
instead of touching EPP. It reached the same 3.5 GHz median but *regressed*
frame-time p999 by ~13-21%: pinning min high keeps the core >= nominal even
during the micro-idle / vsync waits between frames, which on Van Gogh's
shared CPU/GPU TDP perturbs the SMU boost management and costs the extreme
tail. Refuting a write-rate hypothesis (a variant that cut CPPC_REQ writes
~50x still regressed p999) confirmed the lever, not the write volume, was
the cause. Biasing EPP -- exactly what echo performance >
energy_performance_preference does -- reproduces the clean-tail global result
per-core, while leaving min/des/max untouched.

Enabled on the same Civ VI graphics benchmark (interleaved A/B, n=6, Welch),
the per-core mechanism lifts the busy core to a 3.5 GHz median and gives
1%-low fps +31.8% (p=0.014) and frame-time p99 -4.1% (p=0.015) with
frame-time p999 and average fps unchanged -- i.e. the 1%-low/jank win of the
global EPP=performance setting without a p999 regression and without raising
frequency on idle cores or other workloads.

The mechanism:
 - is edge-triggered: the EPP byte is written once when a busy period starts
   and the policy request restored once when it ends, so the CPPC_REQ write
   rate matches EPP=performance's (a couple of writes per busy period);
 - never writes cppc_req_cached, so all other CPPC_REQ writers (limit
   updates, EPP stores, suspend/offline/exit resets) keep operating on the
   policy value and simply clobber the boost, which is re-applied on the next
   activation edge;
 - restores the MSR == cppc_req_cached invariant before every bios_min_perf
   reset (suspend/offline/exit) so the msr_update_perf() value==prev dedup
   cannot skip a reset while the MSR still holds EPP=0;
 - rejects remote update-util callbacks (the hook does local rdmsr/wrmsr) and
   is registered only on MSR (X86_FEATURE_CPPC) systems, since the
   shared-memory CPPC path cannot run from scheduler context.

It is gated behind a runtime-writable module parameter, dynamic_epp, that
defaults to off, so behavior is unchanged unless explicitly enabled with
amd_pstate.dynamic_epp=1 (or echoed to
/sys/module/amd_pstate/parameters/dynamic_epp).
